\section{Branching Rules for ${\widetilde}{G^1}$} \label{branching-rule-section}
First, we present the construction of the principal series representations of ${\widetilde}{G^1}$ following~\cite{mcnamara}. Fix a faithful character $\epsilon : \mu_n\to \mathbb{C}^{\times}$. A representation of ${\widetilde} {G^1}$ is genuine if the central subgroup $\mu_n$ acts by $\epsilon$. Such representations do not factor through representations of ${G^1}$. The construction of principal series representations of ${\widetilde} {G^1}$ is based on the essential fact that ${\widetilde{T^1}}$ is a Heisenberg subgroup, and hence its representations are governed by the Stone-von Neumann theorem, which we state here. See~\cite{mcnamara} for the proof. 
\begin{theo}[Stone-von Neumann]\label{StoneVonNeumman}
	Let $H$ be a Heisenberg group with center $Z(H)$ such that $H/Z(H)$ is finite, and let $\chi$ be a character of $Z(H)$. Suppose that $\ker(\chi)\cap[H,H]=\{1\}$. Then there is a unique (up to isomorphism) irreducible representation $\pi$ of $H$ with central character $\chi$. Let $\mathsf{A}$ be any maximal abelian subgroup of $H$ and let $\chi_0$ be any extension of $\chi$ to $\mathsf{A}$. Then $\pi\cong {\mathrm{Ind}}_{\mathsf{A}}^{H}\chi_0$.
\end{theo}
Note that $[{\widetilde{T^1}}: Z({\widetilde{T^1}})]={\underline{n}}^2<\infty$. Let ${\chi}$ be a genuine character of $Z({\widetilde{T^1}})$, so that ${\chi}|_{\mu_n}=\epsilon$. Thus, $\ker({\chi})\cap [{\widetilde{T^1}},{\widetilde{T^1}}]$ is trivial. Hence Theorem~\ref{StoneVonNeumman} applies: genuine irreducible smooth representations ${\rho}$ of ${\widetilde{T^1}}$ are classified by genuine smooth characters of $Z({\widetilde{T^1}})$. Moreover, $\mathrm{dim}({\rho})=[{\widetilde{T^1}} : {\widetilde}{A^1}]={\underline{n}}$.


Let ${\chi}_{0}$ be a fixed extension of ${\chi}$ to ${A^1}$; so that $({\rho}, {\mathrm{Ind}}_{ {A^1}}^{{\widetilde{T^1}}}{\chi}_0)$ is the unique smooth genuine irreducible  representation of ${\widetilde{T^1}}$ with central character ${\chi}$. Let us again write ${\rho}$ for the genuine smooth irreducible representation of ${\widetilde{T^1}}$, with central character ${\chi}$, extended trivially over ${N^{1}}$ to a representation of ${\widetilde}{B^1}={\widetilde{T^1}}\ltimes{{N^{1}}}$. Then the genuine principal series representation of ${\widetilde}{G^1}$ associated to ${\rho}$ is ${\mathrm{Ind}}_{{\widetilde}{B^1}}^{{\widetilde}{{G^1}}}{{\rho}}$, where ${\mathrm{Ind}}$ denotes the smooth (non-normalized) induction. In the rest of this section, we decompose ${\mathrm{Res}}_{{\widetilde}{K^1}}{\mathrm{Ind}}_{{\widetilde}{B^1}}^{{\widetilde}{{G^1}}}{\rho}$ into irreducible constituents. We drop the adjective ``genuine'' for simplicity.

